        <h1>Symbols * and + in Regular Expressions</h1>
        <p>The symbols * and + are used in regular expressions to indicate that an element can appear zero or more times (*), or one or more times (+), respectively.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h2>Symbol *</h2>
            <p>The symbol * is used to indicate that the preceding element can appear zero or more times. For example:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><code>a*</code> would match "", "a", "aa", "aaa", etc.</li>
                <li><code>\d*</code> would match "", "1", "123", etc.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h2>Symbol +</h2>
            <p>The symbol + is used to indicate that the preceding element can appear one or more times. For example:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><code>a+</code> would match "a", "aa", "aaa", etc., but not "".</li>
                <li><code>\d+</code> would match "1", "123", etc., but not "".</li>
            </ul>
            <p>In summary, the symbol * indicates that the preceding element is optional, while the symbol + indicates that the preceding element is mandatory.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
